    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "816d229c_fe837b13",
        "filename": "go/swarming/autoscaler/autoscaler.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 257,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-07-20T18:28:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My opinion: I think it will be easier to deal with \"starting\" and \"stopping\" statuses rather than waiting for the status to change. I think it will be easier to have alerts on \"instance X has been in \u0027starting\u0027 state for 15 minutes\" rather than dealing with errors returned by waitForStatus/Start/Stop.\n\nOTOH, I\u0027m not sure how we would identify that an instance is in starting or stopping state based on info from Swarming and/or GCE.\n\nI\u0027m also thinking about how we would avoid getting stuck when the process is restarted and we keep trying to call Start on an instance that is starting or Stop on an instance that is stopping. Or even without the process restarting, how to deal with an instance that has failed partway through Start or Stop, where calling the function again fails because it\u0027s not in the expected state.\n\nIt\u0027s possible that the user of Autoscaler doesn\u0027t care about the difference between \"starting\" and \"started\" or between \"stopping\" and \"stopped\". If so, then the in-between states would only be interesting internally. But right now it seems we\u0027re treating \"starting\" and \"stopped\" as the same, which doesn\u0027t seem quite right.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 257,
        "startChar": 21,
        "endLine": 257,
        "endChar": 34
      },
      "revId": "07fc71e329fc6ed27f6da47700ff17faf5543be9",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
